famous than that of the magi. they were' b'renowned as followers of zarathushtra (zoroaster); as the teachers of some of' b'the greatest greek thinkers (pythagoras, democritus, plato); as the wise men' b'who arrived, guided by a star, at the manger of the newborn savior in' b'bethlehem; and as the propagators of a cult of the sun in india. but they were' b'also known as the chaldeans, the priesthood of babylon, known for its occultism;' b'this was perhaps the reason that the term magos had a pejorative sense in greek,' b'like "goes," "expert in the magic arts" (bidez and cumont, indeed, the' b'chaldeans were experts in all types of magical arts, especially astrology, and' b'had a reputation for wisdom as well as knowledge.' b'to understand the reasons for such various and sometimes discordant views, it' b'is necessary to distinguish between the magi of iran proper and the so-called' b'western magi, who were later hellenized. in the achaemenid period both must' b'have been at least in part zoroastrian, but the western magi (those of the' b'iranian diaspora in asia minor, syria, mesopotamia, and armenia), who came in' b'contact with diverse religious traditions, must have, sooner or later and in' b'varying degrees, been influenced by syncretic concepts.' b'the greeks were familiar with both kinds of magi and, depending on their' b'varying concerns, would emphasize one or the other aspect of them. classical' b'historians and geographers, including herodotus and strabo, document their' b'customs, while the philosophers dwell above all on their doctrines: dualism,' b'belief in the hereafter, magian cosmology and cosmogony, and their theology' b'and eschatology. those sources most interested in the doctrines of the magi' b'even speak of zarathushtra as a magus. in doing so they are repeating what the' b'magi themselves said from the median and achaemenid periods, when they adopted' b'zoroastrianism. at that time they embraced zarathushtra as one of their own and' b'placed